D-N-S, or the Domain Name System, translates human-readable names into I-P addresses. Azure provides two services that cover the full spectrum of D-N-S needs. Azure D-N-S lets you host both public D-N-S zones — where Azure becomes the authoritative nameserver for your domain — and private D-N-S zones for name resolution within V-Nets. Azure Traffic Manager is a D-N-S-based global traffic router that directs clients to the best endpoint based on a routing policy. Together these services let you manage your entire D-N-S and global routing strategy without running your own D-N-S infrastructure.

Let us start with Azure D-N-S for public zones.

Azure D-N-S hosts authoritative D-N-S zones. When someone queries www dot contoso dot com, Azure D-N-S answers the query. One important point: Azure D-N-S does not register domains. You register your domain through a registrar such as GoDaddy or Namecheap, and then delegate the zone to Azure D-N-S by updating the registrar's nameserver records to point to the four nameservers Azure assigns to your zone. After D-N-S propagation — which can take minutes to 48 hours — Azure D-N-S becomes authoritative for your domain.

Azure D-N-S supports all standard record types. A records map a hostname to an IPv4 address. A-A-A-A records map to an IPv6 address. C-N-A-M-E records create an alias pointing one hostname to another — for example, www pointing to myapp dot azurewebsites dot net. M-X records define mail exchange servers with a priority. T-X-T records store arbitrary text used for S-P-F email authentication, D-K-I-M, and domain ownership verification. N-S records delegate a subdomain to a different set of nameservers. S-R-V records locate services. P-T-R records provide reverse D-N-S mapping from I-P to hostname. And C-A-A records specify which certificate authorities are allowed to issue certificates for the domain.

Azure D-N-S also supports a special record type called an Alias record. A standard D-N-S limitation is that a C-N-A-M-E cannot be used at the zone apex — the bare domain, contoso dot com without a subdomain — because the apex must contain an S-O-A and N-S record and C-N-A-M-E cannot coexist with those. Azure Alias records solve this by pointing the apex directly to an Azure resource such as a Standard Public I-P, a Load Balancer, a Front Door profile, or a Traffic Manager profile. The alias automatically tracks I-P changes — if the Public I-P address changes, the D-N-S response updates automatically without any manual record changes.

To delegate a subdomain to a child D-N-S zone — for example to let a development team manage their own dev dot contoso dot com zone — you create an N-S record in the parent zone pointing dev dot contoso dot com to the nameservers of the child zone. Azure D-N-S supports this sub-zone delegation natively.

Now let us look at Azure Private D-N-S Zones.

Azure Private D-N-S Zones provide custom name resolution for resources within one or more V-Nets without exposing records publicly and without deploying your own D-N-S servers. You create a private zone such as internal dot contoso dot com, add A records for your private resources, and then create a V-Net link to associate the zone with a V-Net. Resources in any linked V-Net can resolve those records.

A V-Net link has one key optional setting: auto-registration. When auto-registration is enabled, every virtual machine deployed into the linked V-Net automatically gets an A record created in the zone, and that record is deleted when the V-M is removed. Auto-registration only applies to V-Ms — not to private endpoints, load balancers, or other resources.

Private D-N-S zones are critical for private endpoint connectivity. Every Azure P-a-a-S service has a dedicated privatelink dot star zone — for example, privatelink dot blob dot core dot windows dot net for Blob Storage, and privatelink dot database dot windows dot net for Azure S-Q-L. When you create a private endpoint for a storage account, Azure creates an A record in the privatelink zone mapping the storage account's fully qualified domain name to its private I-P. From within a linked V-Net, the name resolves to the private I-P and traffic never leaves the Azure backbone.

In hybrid environments where on-premises D-N-S servers need to resolve Azure private zone names, the Azure D-N-S Private Resolver eliminates the need for custom D-N-S server V-Ms. It has two components. An inbound endpoint is a private I-P in your V-Net that on-premises D-N-S servers can forward queries to — for example, you configure a conditional forwarder on your on-premises D-N-S server so that any query for star dot internal dot contoso dot com is forwarded to the inbound endpoint. An outbound endpoint with a forwarding ruleset forwards queries from Azure V-Nets to on-premises D-N-S servers — for example, queries for on-premises domain names that are not hosted in Azure.

Now let us look at Azure Traffic Manager in depth.

Azure Traffic Manager is a D-N-S-based global traffic router. It does not sit in the data path — it does not proxy or inspect traffic. Instead, when a client makes a D-N-S query for your Traffic Manager profile's D-N-S name, Traffic Manager evaluates its routing policy and health checks, then returns a D-N-S response pointing the client to the best endpoint. The client then connects directly to that endpoint. This means Traffic Manager works with any protocol — not just H-T-T-P.

A Traffic Manager profile has four parts. The D-N-S name is the profile's hostname such as myprofile dot trafficmanager dot net — you point your domain's C-N-A-M-E or Azure Alias record here. The routing method determines how endpoints are selected. The endpoints are the destinations Traffic Manager routes to. And the health monitoring settings define how endpoints are probed.

There are three endpoint types. Azure endpoints are Azure resources with a public I-P or D-N-S name — such as App Service apps, Cloud Services, or Public I-P addresses. External endpoints are any endpoint with an I-P address or fully qualified domain name — including on-premises servers or resources in other clouds. Nested endpoints point to another Traffic Manager profile, allowing you to combine routing methods.

Traffic Manager supports six routing methods. Performance routing directs each client to the endpoint with the lowest measured D-N-S latency from the client's location — ideal for active-active multi-region deployments where you want the best user experience. Weighted routing distributes traffic proportionally by a weight value between 1 and 1000 — use this for canary deployments or gradual migrations. Priority routing sends all traffic to the highest-priority endpoint and fails over to lower-priority endpoints only when higher ones are unhealthy — the classic active-passive disaster recovery pattern. Geographic routing directs clients based on the geographic origin of the D-N-S query — essential for data residency compliance where users in specific regions must be served by specific deployments. Multivalue routing returns multiple healthy endpoint addresses in a single D-N-S response — the client chooses which to use, providing client-side redundancy. Subnet routing maps specific client I-P address ranges to specific endpoints — useful for testing or for routing corporate network users differently from public internet users.

Traffic Manager probes each endpoint on a configurable interval — either 10 seconds for fast probing or 30 seconds for normal probing. If an endpoint fails a configurable number of consecutive probes, Traffic Manager marks it as Degraded and stops including it in D-N-S responses. Once the endpoint recovers, Traffic Manager resumes routing to it.

Failover speed is bounded by the D-N-S T-T-L that Traffic Manager sets on its responses. The default is 60 seconds. Clients cache the D-N-S result for the T-T-L duration, so if an endpoint fails, clients that already cached the old response will continue sending traffic there until the T-T-L expires. Lowering the T-T-L to zero enables near-instant failover but significantly increases D-N-S query volume — balance these trade-offs based on your recovery time requirements.

For complex scenarios you can nest Traffic Manager profiles. For example, a parent profile uses Priority routing with a child profile A as the primary endpoint and a child profile B as the failover. Child profile A uses Performance routing to distribute traffic across active regions globally. Child profile B uses Weighted routing to distribute across a disaster recovery region. This lets you combine multiple routing strategies into a single coherent policy.

Let us now look at how custom domains are set up with Azure services.

For an App Service with a subdomain, you create a C-N-A-M-E in Azure D-N-S pointing www dot contoso dot com to myapp dot azurewebsites dot net, plus a T-X-T verification record that App Service uses to confirm you own the domain. For the apex domain, you use an Azure Alias record pointing contoso dot com to the Standard Public I-P or Front Door profile attached to the App Service.

For Azure Front Door, a C-N-A-M-E points your subdomain to the Front Door's azurefd dot net hostname. For the apex, an Alias record in Azure D-N-S points contoso dot com to the Front Door profile. Front Door can also issue and auto-renew a managed T-L-S certificate for your custom domain — eliminating manual certificate management.

For Traffic Manager, you create a C-N-A-M-E pointing your subdomain to the trafficmanager dot net profile hostname, or an Alias record at the apex.

To summarise. Azure D-N-S hosts authoritative public zones — delegate at your registrar by updating N-S records. Use Alias records instead of C-N-A-M-Es at the zone apex to point to Azure resources. Use Private D-N-S Zones for V-Net name resolution, auto-registration of V-M hostnames, and private endpoint D-N-S. Use the D-N-S Private Resolver in hybrid environments to forward queries between on-premises D-N-S and Azure private zones without custom D-N-S servers. Use Traffic Manager for D-N-S-based global routing of any protocol — choose Performance for best user experience in active-active, Priority for active-passive failover, Geographic for data residency, and Weighted for gradual migrations. Remember that failover speed is T-T-L-dependent — tune the T-T-L for your recovery time objective.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure S-Q-L Database and Cosmos D-B — Azure's managed relational and multi-model N-o-S-Q-L database services.
